It's a bit of a rarity; only manufactured from 1948 to 1954, with 43,123 made. It was designed as a "first rifle" for kids. Only very few were target models with the peep sight,  This was the only Winchester single shot bolt action that cocked automatically on opening the bolt. Opening the bolt engages the safety automatically; it must be released to fire the gun after the bolt is engaged. Earlier bolts were straight-handled, later ones used swept-back handles.

title: For Sale:  Discontinued .44 Magnum Marlin 1894C
postcontent:
[OR BEST OFFER.]

I bought this handsome monster in 1991 but it sat forlorn in various closets till the week before last, when I finally took it to the range to finally fire it. A mere 20 rounds suggests this .44 magnum is just too much gun for me: there isn't much recoil but the very loud BOOM makes me flinch. And my bills were more than I'd expected so...

It's in great shape, with a cross-bar safety, a blued finish, the standard walnut stock, a hammer extension I see no need to remove, and a Micro-Groove barrel. (Wikipedia says "in the mid-1990s, Marlin changed the .357 and .44 barrels from 12-groove-or-more 'Micro-Groove' rifling to 6-groove 'Ballard' style rifling.") The only things wrong with this gun are that the folding leaf rear sight somehow broke off, and now there are a couple ugly but not fatal scratches on/near the sight base from where I tried and failed to install a replacement (see second photo).

UPDATE: I went ahead and ordered another folding leaf rear sight from Midway; they say it shipped and will be here within a week. If somebody buys my rifle before then I'll mail it to you quickly to complete my end of the deal.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Ground Rules
postcontent:
Just in case not everyone was given the same lessons in classified firearms:

- If ANY firearm was PURCHASED, period, it is no longer NEW! Shot or not, when you bought that sucker, it's no longer a new firearm.
- Following rule 1, since it's no longer NEW, it will not bring a NEW price tag. 
- SALE is a noun. SELL is a verb. Please establish which one you're using. You're 4th grader would probably slap you in the mouth for being an idiot. 
- If you bump your listing more than twice, no one wants your crap. Take it somewhere else.

An example if provided below for the individual that needs a little extra help,

NOT GOOD:

Hello, 

Listed is a Smith n Wessun SD 9VE, Brand New, only shot once, that I would like to SALE for 400.00. I would take a fully tricked out colt AR-15 as trade, plus boot from you.
